e been thinking about work-related problems where any decisions I take as a result of my thinking will have consequences to be evaluated by others."), mdx("hr", null), mdx("p", null, "What causes the stress that makes it \u201Cwork\u201D is a combination of two factors. First, since you define what to do, there are no natural limits. You can define your work to be as simple or complicated as you like. Second, since the reaction of an unpredictable external party is going to determine how you feel about the work, there is a reason for you to endlessly work to try and lower the anxiety about the unpredictability. In other words, there is an infinitely-stretchable component to the work (the definition), and a fundamentally unknowable component to its consequences (the external reaction)."), mdx("ul", null, mdx("li", {
